			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008</a> paper:</span><br><i>Engineering Languages for Specifying Product-Derivation Processes in Software Product Lines</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/PabloSánchez.html">Pablo Sánchez</a>, <a href="../profile/NeilLoughran.html">Neil Loughran</a>, <a href="../profile/LidiaFuentes.html">Lidia Fuentes</a>, <a href="../profile/AlessandroFabricioGarcia.html">Alessandro Fabricio Garcia</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_13">10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_13</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagM">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> It designs languages to specify product-derivation processes, directly addressing variability in software product lines.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The derivation-process specification is realized as a DSL tailored to SPL derivation concerns.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It involves language design decisions for capturing derivation-process concepts and constraints.
</li></ul></li></ul>
